<article>
    <h1>How to avoid staph skin in&#xAD;fec&#xAD;tions</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20200821/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-08-21"><time>2020-08-21</time></a>
        - <span>HOME</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>• Main­tain good hand</p>
    <p>hy­giene.</p>
    <p>• Clean all cuts and bruises with an­ti­sep­tics or soap, and visit a doc­tor if you see a boil form­ing.</p>
    <p>• Avoid shar­ing tow­els or other per­sonal items to pro­tect your­self from ex­po­sure to dif­fer­ent bac­te­ria.</p>
    <p>• Do not en­ter the sea if you</p>
    <p>have wounds or bro­ken skin. • Keep wounds cov­ered to pre­vent bac­te­ria from spread­ing.</p>
    <p>• Avoid ar­eas known to have many in­sects and use in­sect re­pel­lent.</p>
    <p>• Shower, or at least wash your hands and feet, be­fore and after en­ter­ing the wa­ter. • Al­ways wash your hands, or wear gloves, be­fore ap­ply­ing oint­ments to wounds, to pre­vent the spread of bac­te­ria.</p>
    <p>• Wash clothes and linen in hot wa­ter, as staphy­lo­coc­cus au­reus can sur­vive on fab­ric that has not been prop­erly washed.</p>
    <p>SOURCES: Dr Paul Tam­byah, Dr Gavin O’Neill, The Mayo Clinic</p>


